---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';
import CaseStudyFigure from '../components/CaseStudyFigure.astro';

const img = (file: string) => `images/case-studies/des-sys/${file}`;

const nav = [
  { label: 'Overview', href: '#overview' },
  { label: 'Impact & Process', href: '#impact' },
  { label: 'AI Workflow', href: '#workflow' },
  { label: 'Reflection', href: '#reflection' },
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
  title="Design Systems"
  heading="Bridging design and code with AI"
  role="Product Designer"
  team="Intuit Design Systems"
  timeline="Jan 2026 – Present"
  projectType="Product, Design Systems"
  nav={nav}
  commentId="case-study-des-sys"
>
  <section id="overview" data-comment-id="des-sys-overview">
    <h3>context</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      The Intuit Design System (IDS) supports designers and engineers across Intuit through a shared
      library of components and design tokens.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      As the design system evolves, maintaining alignment between design and code becomes
      increasingly difficult.
    </p>

    <h3>why this matters</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <h2>Design handoff less reliable</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Handoff is less reliable if components are not 1-to-1 between prototypes and
          implementation.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h2>Hardcoded values bypass tokens</h2>
        <p class="lead">
          Use of hardcoded values instead of tokens in components bypasses global theme updates.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h3>opportunity</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I explored how AI can empower designers to take greater ownership of implementation while
      maintaining quality and consistency.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="impact" data-comment-id="des-sys-impact">
    <h3>How small changes scale</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I updated 3 (+ more in progress) core components across the design system. Just one component
      can have a large systematic impact.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">For the checkbox component:</p>
    <div class="case-study-stats">
      <div class="case-study-stat">
        <strong>355k+</strong>
        <span>instances of checkbox in Figma</span>
      </div>
      <div class="case-study-stat">
        <strong>143</strong>
        <span>business units use checkbox in code</span>
      </div>
      <div class="case-study-stat">
        <strong>164</strong>
        <span>design teams use checkbox</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      src={img('ids-project-hero.png')}
      alt="Intuit Design Systems project — checkbox component at scale"
      caption="IDS component work at Intuit"
    />

    <h3>What do token adjustments look like</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Some token adjustments bring alignment between design and code. Others are adjusted to align
      with documentation. In the example below, the use of input-label as the colour token is
      incorrect for its use case regardless of the alignment between design and code.
    </p>
    <CaseStudyFigure
      src={img('token-alignment-input-label.png')}
      alt="Before and after aligning input label colour token from --input-label to --text-primary"
      caption="Token alignment — label colour consolidated to --text-primary"
    />
    <CaseStudyFigure
      src={img('token-alignment-font-weight.png')}
      alt="Before and after aligning checkbox label font weight between design and code"
      caption="Token alignment — font weight synced to --font-weight-component"
    />
  </section>

  <section id="workflow" data-comment-id="des-sys-workflow">
    <h3>audit process</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Previously, identifying an issue and implementing a fix required separate design and
      engineering workflows. Below is the workflow that designers can own in the process.
    </p>
    <div class="case-study-figure-row">
      <CaseStudyFigure
        src={img('audit-workflow-before.png')}
        alt="Previous audit workflow with separate design and engineering handoffs"
        caption="Before — separate design and engineering workflows"
      />
      <CaseStudyFigure
        src={img('audit-workflow-after.png')}
        alt="Designer-owned audit workflow with AI-assisted review, Storybook preview, and PR"
        caption="After — designer-owned workflow with AI-assisted steps"
      />
    </div>
    <p class="lead">AI didn't replace review or decision-making.</p>
    <p class="lead">
      Instead, it enabled me to participate more directly in implementation, reducing dependency on
      engineering bandwidth for lower-risk updates while maintaining quality.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="reflection" data-comment-id="des-sys-reflection">
    <h3>Reflection</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      Nothing is too small. Maintaining the integrity of a design system starts at the pixel level.
      By leveraging AI throughout the workflow, I was able to move beyond identifying problems and
      contribute directly to implementation, validation, and shipping while maintaining confidence
      in the quality of the work.
    </p>

    <h3 class="!mt-12">next steps</h3>
    <p class="lead">
      I'm interested in refining the auditing skill to detect deeper system-level inconsistencies,
      such as incorrect or inconsistent token usage that may not be caught by surface-level checks
      as I move through the components within the design system.
    </p>
  </section>
</CaseStudyLayout>
